age\" would have no scheme and no netloc, so it's internal. A URL like \"//example.com\" (protocol-relative) would have no scheme but would have a netloc, so it's external. My validation logic checks `if parsed.scheme or parsed.netloc`, which catches most external URLs—if either is present, it's rejected. Internal URLs would typically be relative paths starting with \"/\" or simple relative references without any domain information.\n\nThe approach is to parse the target URL and reject anything with a scheme or netloc component, allowing only relative paths. The implementation uses Flask with a redirect endpoint that validates the target URL before redirecting, returning a 400 error for external URLs and a 302 redirect for valid internal ones.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4664,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4664},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dfc8aeae-e186-40bf-b62f-f018aa602f4d","uuid":"0bdcb028-9ef1-4a48-925f-250280ed3af6","request_id":"req_011CbdLvUJstfg6rMjSi96hX"}
